[Student "S"]
{South's 3\S bid is a limit raise showing 10-12 points and good trump support. North is to play 6\S. East leads the \HQ.

This \D holding is the first example shown in the introduction.

With one certain \H loser you cannot afford to lose a \D also. You could guess which way to finesse and be correct half of the time. But an elimination play will work ALL of the time.

Win the first trick and play \SA, \SK. Trumps split 2-1.

Next play three rounds of \Cs to eliminate that suit from both your and dummy's hand.

With all the eliminations completed you are ready for the throw-in. Lead a \H from either hand. One of the defenders will win, (you don't care which), and will be end-played.

The defender who won the last trick cannot lead a trump because he has none. If he leads a \H or a \C you will get a ruff-sluff, ruffing in one hand while discarding a \D loser from the other. If he leads a \D you will get the free finesse you were hoping for all along.

If you finesse West for the \DQ you make the contract, but if you finesse East for that card you go down.

With an elimination play you make it no matter who holds the Queen.}
[Play "W"]HQ

